ke to think that I give the players around me a more accurate perception of what a wizard can actually offer a group.  I do think that that is really the main problem in the game; that the perception of class X has little value.<br>
<br>
I have to disagree with the person that said that its NOT ok for a wizard to be OOM after killing a few mobs fast.  Your arguement to support this was that these situations don't happen very often.  I have a couple of responses to this.<br>
<br>
First, even if you don't get into the situations where a quite mob kill is required very often, in the rare times it does happen and your wizard comes through to save the group, you have shown your value.  If that 1 pull out of 100 goes bad and you save your group from a CR, thats well worth it.<br>
<br>
Second, if you are finding that your group is never getting into those situations, your group is not performing to its maximum potential.  I do realize that many players would rather just stare at their screen and take as little risk as possible but the fact remains, your group won't be doing as much as it could.  Quite simply you can handle situations with a wizard than without. For many people, myself especially, taking on these situations is where the fun is at and I think it seperates the mice from the men.<br>
<br>
So my advice is to get your group to learn how to survive these situations and perhaps the perception of wizards will begin to change.  I know I have never had a problem with wizard perception with anyone that I have played with. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=siryakk>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 156<br> <font color=#ffffff>(11/15/02 11:23 am)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Perception</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>First, even if you don't get into the situations where a quite mob kill is required very often, in the rare times it does happen and your wizard comes through to save the group, you have shown your value. If that 1 pull out of 100 goes bad and you save your group from a CR, thats well worth it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Here is a question.  If that wizard was doing 50% more damage per hour, dropping mobs faster, having higher mana on the other casters, would that 1 in 100 bad pull become just another pull?<br>
<br>
Wizard fast damage isn't fast enough.  How long does it take for a wizard to burn down a L 60 creature -- 20 to 30 seconds?  A pull where people are alive for 20 to 30 seconds after things go bad isn't a bad pull.<br>
<br>
Evac is a better tool in that situation, if things are really bad -- it only takes 8 seconds for evac to work.  And a pull where nobody dies in 8 seconds is also not that bad of a pull.<br>
<br>
Heck, most PoP mobs can't be taken down with a manaburn, let alone normal chain nuking.  How often do you manaburn in an xp group?<br>
<br>
Make manaburn more usable, and then you have an arguement.  Ie, how about a manaburn that doesn't use your mana, just does damage based on how much mana you have?  Or, a manaburn that does damage based on your mana capacity, irregardness of your current mana level, then drains your mana?<br>
<br>
Then, you could burn down 1 mob every 2 hours, saving the party, and at the same time mantain a decent DPS over the rest of the 2 hours.<br>
